03284nam a2200565Ia 9789815203271DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20242024si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898152032717 a10.1355/97898152032712doi  a(DE-B1597)690338  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 7aPOL0080002bisacsh04a324.2593072231 aColombier, Alexandra, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHow Thailand’s Move Forward Party’s Fandom Strategy Shaped the 2023 General Election /cAlexandra Colombier. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (17 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tFOREWORD -- tEXECUTIVE SUMMARY -- tINTRODUCTION -- tTHE MAKING OF DOM SOM -- tINVESTING IN TIKTOK -- tACHIEVING CELEBRITY STATUS -- tTHE CONSTRAINTS AND LIMITATIONS OF DOM SOM -- tCONCLUSION0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe concept of political fandom, the state of being fans of a politician or of a political party, played a crucial role during Thailand’s General Election in 2023. Fandom contributed to the popularity on social media of politicians, such as Pita Limjaroenrat, the Move Forward Party’s leader and prime ministerial candidate. The strategies involved in achieving celebrity status for politicians are varied. This paper provides a case study of the factors behind the success of Pita and the Move Forward Party and contrasts these with reasons why Pita’s key political opponents were less effective. It argues that the digital age and the transcendence of politics into pop culture, where celebrity status and fandom can drive electoral outcomes, signify a profound shift in democratic participation, political engagement and the very fabric of Thai politics. While fandom has become a stream in participatory democracy, it also highlights the polarized and temperamental nature of Thailand’s contemporary hyper-partisan political scene.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aElectionszThailand. 0aFans (Persons)zThailand. 0aPolitical partieszThailand. 4aCampaigns & Elections. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Campaigns & Elections.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981520327140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789815203271423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789815203271/original  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles